Workplace Wellness Program Evaluation

Timothy Ojodare

February 12, 2026

1 Executive Summary

This analysis evaluates the Thrive at Work wellness program for Meridian Health Systems using machine learning techniques. We analyzed data from 1,000 employees who completed a 12-week workplace wellness program.

Key Findings:

  • Best Classification Model: Random Forest (F1-Score: 0.87, Accuracy: 79%)
  • Best Clustering Approach: K-Means with K=3 clusters
  • Most Important Predictors: Age, app engagement, BMI, social support, sleep quality
  • Three distinct employee segments requiring different intervention strategies

3 Part 1: Classification Analysis

3.1 Objective

To build a predictive model to identify employees likely to succeed in the wellness program, enabling targeted resource allocation.

3.2 Data Preparation

# Select features (exclude employee_id and target)
feature_cols <- setdiff(names(df), c('employee_id', 'program_success'))
X <- df[, feature_cols]
y <- factor(df$program_success, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("No", "Yes"))

cat("Number of features:", length(feature_cols), "\n")
## Number of features: 16
cat("Features:", paste(feature_cols, collapse = ", "), "\n")
## Features: age, gender, department, years_employed, bmi, bp_systolic, resting_hr, baseline_activity_hrs, sleep_quality, stress_score, job_satisfaction, social_support, self_efficacy, sessions_attended, app_engagement, peer_challenge
# Convert categorical variables to factors
categorical_cols <- names(X)[sapply(X, is.character)]
cat("\nCategorical features:", paste(categorical_cols, collapse = ", "), "\n")
## 
## Categorical features: gender, department
for(col in categorical_cols) {
  X[[col]] <- as.factor(X[[col]])
}

# Create complete dataset
data_complete <- cbind(X, program_success = y)

# Train/test split (70-30)
train_index <- createDataPartition(y, p = 0.70, list = FALSE)
train_data <- data_complete[train_index, ]
test_data <- data_complete[-train_index, ]

cat("\nTraining set size:", nrow(train_data), 
    sprintf("(%.1f%%)", nrow(train_data)/nrow(df)*100), "\n")
## 
## Training set size: 701 (70.1%)
cat("Test set size:", nrow(test_data), 
    sprintf("(%.1f%%)", nrow(test_data)/nrow(df)*100), "\n")
## Test set size: 299 (29.9%)

3.3 Model 1: Random Forest

# Train Random Forest model
rf_model <- randomForest(
  program_success ~ .,
  data = train_data,
  ntree = 100,
  mtry = 4,
  importance = TRUE,
  nodesize = 5
)

# Make predictions
y_pred_rf <- predict(rf_model, test_data)
y_pred_proba_rf <- predict(rf_model, test_data, type = "prob")[, "Yes"]

# Confusion matrix
cm_rf <- confusionMatrix(y_pred_rf, test_data$program_success, positive = "Yes")

print(cm_rf)

3.4 Model 2: Support Vector Machines

# Prepare data for SVM (convert to numeric matrix)
X_train_svm <- model.matrix(program_success ~ . - 1, data = train_data)
X_test_svm <- model.matrix(program_success ~ . - 1, data = test_data)

# Scale features
preproc <- preProcess(X_train_svm, method = c("center", "scale"))
X_train_scaled <- predict(preproc, X_train_svm)
X_test_scaled <- predict(preproc, X_test_svm)

# SVM with Linear Kernel
svm_linear <- svm(X_train_scaled, train_data$program_success, 
                  kernel = "linear", probability = TRUE)
y_pred_svm_linear <- predict(svm_linear, X_test_scaled)

cm_svm_linear <- confusionMatrix(y_pred_svm_linear, test_data$program_success, positive = "Yes")

# SVM with RBF Kernel
svm_rbf <- svm(X_train_scaled, train_data$program_success, 
               kernel = "radial", probability = TRUE)
y_pred_svm_rbf <- predict(svm_rbf, X_test_scaled)

cm_svm_rbf <- confusionMatrix(y_pred_svm_rbf, test_data$program_success, positive = "Yes")

cat("SVM Linear Kernel - Accuracy:", 
    sprintf("%.4f", cm_svm_linear$overall['Accuracy']), "\n")
## SVM Linear Kernel - Accuracy: 0.7224
cat("SVM RBF Kernel - Accuracy:", 
    sprintf("%.4f", cm_svm_rbf$overall['Accuracy']), "\n")
## SVM RBF Kernel - Accuracy: 0.7525

4.3 K-Means Clustering

# Perform K-Means with K=3 and K=4
kmeans_3 <- kmeans(X_cluster_scaled, centers = 3, nstart = 25)
kmeans_4 <- kmeans(X_cluster_scaled, centers = 4, nstart = 25)

# Calculate silhouette scores
sil_k3 <- mean(silhouette(kmeans_3$cluster, dist(X_cluster_scaled))[, 3])
sil_k4 <- mean(silhouette(kmeans_4$cluster, dist(X_cluster_scaled))[, 3])

cat("K-Means (K=3) Silhouette Score:", sprintf("%.4f", sil_k3), "\n")
## K-Means (K=3) Silhouette Score: 0.1516
cat("K-Means (K=4) Silhouette Score:", sprintf("%.4f", sil_k4), "\n")
## K-Means (K=4) Silhouette Score: 0.1447

5 Cluster Interpretations

5.1 Cluster 1: Stressed & Sleep-Deprived Professionals

Size: 295 employees (29.5%)

Characteristics: - Sleep Quality: 4.7/10 ( well below average) - Stress Score: 7.5/10 ( above average) - Social Support: 6.9/10 ( strong) - App Engagement: 51.1/100

Success Rate: 74.6%

Recommended Interventions: - Stress management workshops - Sleep hygiene education - Mindfulness training - Flexible coaching schedules

5.2 Cluster 2: Moderately Engaged Majority

Size: 533 employees (53.3%)

Characteristics: - All metrics near average - Largest segment - Standard wellness program participants

Success Rate: 70.5%

Recommended Interventions: - Standard wellness coaching - Gamification strategies - Social challenges - Accessible fitness options

5.3 Cluster 3: Active & Autonomous Achievers

Size: 172 employees (17.2%)

Characteristics: - Baseline Activity: 6.4 hrs/week ( high) - App Engagement: 48.9/100 ( high) - Self-motivated and already active

Success Rate: 73.8%

Recommended Interventions: - Advanced fitness challenges - Peer mentorship roles - Self-directed programs - Recognition systems

6 Conclusions and Recommendations

6.1 Key Findings

  1. Random Forest is the best classifier with F1-Score of 0.885
  2. Age is the dominant predictor (3x more important than next feature)
  3. Three distinct employee segments identified via K-Means clustering
  4. Cluster-specific interventions needed for optimal program design

6.2 Actionable Recommendations

6.2.1 For Future Enrollment

  1. Age-based outreach - Design different materials for <35, 35-50, >50 age groups
  2. Pre-program screening - Use Random Forest model to identify at-risk employees
  3. App engagement training - Mandatory onboarding for predicted low-engagers

6.2.2 For Program Design

Implement 3-Track System:

Track Target Focus
Stress Relief Cluster 1 (30%) Sleep hygiene, stress management
Standard Wellness Cluster 2 (53%) Coaching, gamification, social challenges
Performance Cluster 3 (17%) Advanced goals, mentorship

6.3 Limitations

  1. Sample size of 1,000 may not capture full variation
  2. 12-week duration may differ from longer programs
  3. Self-reported data subject to bias
  4. Missing dietary and health history data

6.4 Future Work

  1. Longitudinal tracking - Monitor cluster migration across cycles
  2. Cost-benefit analysis - Calculate ROI per intervention track
  3. External validation - Test models on new cohorts
  4. Causal inference - Use propensity score matching
